{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563556"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.4,0.42,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9505"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52521"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8185"},{"type":"tags","id":"11127"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22440"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after a syncopal episode at home. She reports nine weeks of amenorrhoea and has had intermittent vaginal bleeding and right-sided abdominal pain for the past two days. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended with generalised tenderness, maximal in the right upper quadrant. Vaginal examination reveals cervical excitation tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003Cbr /\u003EHaemoglobin: 82 g/L (115-160)\u003Cbr /\u003EBeta-human chorionic gonadotropin: 8,500 IU/L\u003Cbr /\u003EPoint-of-care ultrasound shows large volume free fluid in the abdomen and pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmergency laparoscopy reveals a pregnancy in the upper right uterine wall junction where the fallopian tube joins the uterine cavity with active arterial bleeding. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate surgical management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oophorectomy","Salpingectomy","Cornual wedge resection","Hysterectomy","Salpingostomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of haemodynamic compromise (syncope, tachycardia, hypotension) and a positive pregnancy test, highly suspicious for a ruptured cornual ectopic pregnancy. The location of pain in the right upper quadrant and laparoscopic findings confirm a cornual ectopic pregnancy, which carries a high risk of life-threatening haemorrhage due to the rich vascularity of this region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECornual wedge resection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate surgical management. This involves excision of the cornual region of the uterus containing the ectopic pregnancy while preserving the remainder of the uterus. This approach is necessary because the rich vascularity of the cornual region puts these patients at high risk of catastrophic haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalpingectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for a tubal ectopic pregnancy but would not address a cornual ectopic, which is located within the muscular wall of the uterus where the fallopian tube joins the uterine cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalpingostomy\u003C/strong\u003E, like salpingectomy, would be insufficient for managing a cornual ectopic pregnancy as it only addresses the fallopian tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly aggressive in this case. While it may be necessary in cases of uncontrollable haemorrhage or extensive uterine damage, cornual wedge resection is usually sufficient and preserves fertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the ectopic pregnancy and would unnecessarily remove normal ovarian tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing cornual wedge resection, these patients should be counselled about the risk of uterine rupture in future pregnancies and the need for caesarean delivery, as the cornual region is a common site of uterine rupture during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cornual ectopic pregnancy requires urgent surgical management due to high risk of catastrophic haemorrhage.","Cornual wedge resection is the preferred surgical approach for cornual ectopic pregnancy.","Syncope in early pregnancy should raise suspicion for ruptured ectopic pregnancy."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy (Green-top Guideline No. 21). BJOG. 2016;123(13):e15\u2013e55. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1111/1471-0528.14189"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52521"}